result.execSummary:
The defendant Trevor Maloney was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Attempt Retail Theft - Intentionally Take (<=$500), a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.50(1m)(b).
  • Possession of THC, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(e).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

11:15 AM - Def in court w/ Atty Timothy J Guth.  Def in custody.  Brian K. Barton appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
BARTON: hoping that he would take advantage of what supervision  has to offer and he didn't. Fortunate for him they are only revoking this one case and not the other. He was given the chance by this court at sentencing and you gave him the chance for 973.015 and that wasn't enough. The only thing left is a jail sentence but how long. Asking the court to giver 6 mos on each w/. some time of no release and then some on EM to aid his PO on the other case. At some time he has to get it and he just can't do things his way. GUTH: TWB put him on probation just  12/8 w/ conditions and 973.015 trmt. He's been in jail for 79 days now. DEF: I will be living w/ the man who took guardianship of me when I was younger. I plan on getting out and signing up for TC. I have 2 more tests to get my GED. CRT: you have a felony probation b/f TWB that the DOC is letting the supervision con't  which is a huge advantage to you.  If that probation would be revoked you lose the eligibility for expungement. You lost the chance to have these charges expunged but they don't have the same long term effects as a felony. Any violations you can be returned to jail to serve all or a portion of the sentence w/o release
SENTENCE: as to each count - def to serve 120 days CJ concurrent w/ credit for 79 days on each - can have EM for the balance of the sentence eff 10 AM on 12/23
